cs.CV, cs.LG, cs.NE, cs.AI, cs.HC

This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it describes a supervised skullstripping algorithm that utilizes three trained fully convolutional neural networks to segment 2D T1-weighted slices in axial, coronal, and sagittal views. 

It is also likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-categories as it uses convolutional neural networks for the segmentation task. 

The paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as it describes a specialized infant MRI skullstripping algorithm that is necessary due to the significant size and shape variability of the head and the brain in that age range. 

Finally, it may belong to the Human-Computer Interaction (cs.HC) sub-category as accurate skullstripping is a critical component in neuroimage processing pipelines, which are often used in clinical settings where human-computer interaction is important.
